{"cursor":"19770","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn mathematics, the 'absolute value' (or 'modulus') x }} of a real number \nis the non-negative value of  without regard to its sign. Namely, x = x}}\nfor a positive , x = âx}} for a negative , and 0 = 0}}. For example,\nthe absolute value of 3 is 3, and the absolute value of â3 is also 3.\nThe absolute value of a number may be thought of as its distance from zero.\n\nGeneralizations of the absolute value for real numbers occur in a wide variety\nof mathematical settings. For example an absolute value is also defined for the\ncomplex numbers, the quaternions, ordered rings, fields and vector spaces. The\nabsolute value is closely related to the notions of magnitude, distance, and\nnorm in various mathematical and physical contexts.\n","linknr":414,"url":"Absolute_value","recorded":1362374590,"links":72,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","algebra","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","littré"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Elementary special functions"],"headings":["Terminology and notation","Definition and properties","Absolute value function","Distance","Generalizations","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/70/Khoang_cach_tren_duong_thang_thuc.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/c/b/8cb53c58631c94cc12e446129810669d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/6/2/3622f6883b63ba71c44e2e909d4afe97.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/5/a/25af6c290a4af34e9f5c61c459ec33d3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/f/b/cfbf4981120811c431db54bfd6a80dd7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/5/d/85d6315581e1f0b396f62ce3817ea9d7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/6/5/e65854add7fa0e14ce9877552cc7eb50.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/3/4/a3445e3e29bb2cb81b0db1aa46a81aa1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/b/e/0be450c683079a688ca2ee6709191e2e.png","//upl